nt, not recognized as revenue for the Space segment, highlighting the integrated operational model.\n\n### 3. **Direct Benefits to the AI Segment (Orbital AI Compute)**\nThe text identifies **"AI compute"** as SpaceX\'s next target "trillion-dollar market," and Starship is the critical infrastructure to realize it.\n*   **Enabling Orbital Data Centers:** The company\'s vision for "orbital AI compute" requires launching data centers into space. The document states, **"We expect to leverage our rockets and satellites for massive orbital deployments of AI infrastructure."**\n*   **Required Scale:** The scale needed for orbital compute is staggering: **"Deployment of 100 gigawatts per year... will require thousands of launches per year and the transport of approximately one million metric tons to orbit annually."** Starship\'s fully reusable design and massive payload capacity (targeting 100-200 metric tons) is positioned as the only system capable of achieving this scale in the near term.\n*   **Future Allocation:** Similar to the Connectivity segment, SpaceX **"expect[s] to allocate a significant amount [of launch capacity] to our AI segment in the future."**\n\n### 4. **Technical and Financial Synergies**\n*   **Proven Reliability:** The reliability of SpaceX\'s existing satellite platform (Starlink) under launch stress is cited as a key advantage for evolving "connectivity satellites into AI compute satellites." The experience and data from thousands of Falcon 9 launches directly inform the development of Starship and future orbital hardware.\n*   **Vertical Integration:** The company\'s control over the entire stack—from rocket design and manufacturing (Starship) to satellite production and ground station operations—creates a unique competitive moat. This allows them to **"tailor [satellites] for specific orbital compute applications"** and optimize the entire system.\n\n**In summary, Starship is not merely a product of the Space segment; it is the central piece of