2026-06-10 15:53:15,088 DEBUG Tool call: submit_final_result({'final_result': '\n## Starship R&D Reallocation: Space Segment Adjusted EBITDA Impact\n\n### Reported Space Segment FY2025 Financials\n\n| Line Item | FY2025 ($M) |\n|---|---|\n| Segment Revenue | $4,086 |\n| Starship R&D (within segment) | $3,004 |\n| Income (Loss) from Operations | $(657) |\n| **Add back:** D&A | $757 |\n| **Add back:** SBC | $515 |\n| **Add back:** Impairment | $38 |\n| **Reported Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | **$653** |\n| **Reported Adj. EBITDA Margin** | **16.0%** |\n\n### Pro Forma: Starship R&D as Unallocated Corporate Expense\n\nIf the $3,004M of Starship R&D were removed from the Space segment and treated as an unallocated corporate expense:\n\n| Line Item | FY2025 ($M) |\n|---|---|\n| Reported Income (Loss) from Operations | $(657) |\n| Add back: Starship R&D removed from segment | +$3,004 |\n| **Pro Forma Income from Operations** | **$2,347** |\n| **Add back:** D&A | $757 |\n| **Add back:** SBC | $515 |\n| **Add back:** Impairment | $38 |\n| **Pro Forma Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | **$3,657** |\n| **Pro Forma Adj. EBITDA Margin** | **89.5%** |\n\n### Result\n\n**Pro forma Space Segment Adjusted EBITDA = $3,657M**, compared to the reported $653M — a **$3,004M uplift** (a ~460% increase).\n\n---\n\n### What This Indicates About Segment-Level Profitability Presentation\n\n**1. Starship R&D Dominates the Space Segment P&L**\n\nThe $3,004M in Starship R&D consumes nearly the entire Adjusted EBITDA that the Space segment would otherwise generate ($3,657M pre-Starship vs. $653M reported). It is the single largest expense line item and turns what would be an extraordinarily profitable segment into one reporting only modest profitability. Without Starship R&D, the Space segment\'s Adjusted EBITDA margin of **89.5%** would rival the most profitable defense/aerospace companies in history.\n\n**2. Cross-Subsidy Disguised as Segment Cost**\n\nThe filing explicitly acknowledges that Starship is "the key enabler of our long-term growth strategy by unlocking entirely new categories of missions" for the **Connectivity** segment (enabling V3 Starlink satellite deployment at 20× current capacity) and the **AI** segment (enabling orbital compute infrastructure requiring "thousands of launches per year"). Yet 100% of Starship development costs are allocated to the Space segment. This creates an implicit cross-subsidy: the Space segment\'s reported profitability is depressed to fund infrastructure that primarily benefits other segments\' future revenue growth.\n\n**3. Vintage-Dependent Comparability**\n\nThe filing notes that Starship R&D surged from $1,835M in FY2024 to $3,004M in FY2025 (+64%) as SpaceX "accelerated [its] timeline for Starship development." Upon Starship\'s commercialization, costs will shift from R&D expense to capitalized/depreciated cost of revenue within the Space segment. This means the Space segment\'s Adjusted EBITDA margin will show a structural upward shift when commercialization occurs — not because operations improved, but because the cost classification changes. Investors should not compare pre- and post-commercialization margins without adjusting for this accounting reclassification.\n\n**4. Implications for Valuation**\n\nAn investor analyzing the Space segment on reported Adjusted EBITDA ($653M on $4,086M revenue) would value it as a moderately profitable, capital-intensive launch business. The same investor adjusting Starship R&D to corporate overhead would see a segment generating $3,657M of Adjusted EBITDA — a foundational technology platform with monopoly-level margins. The allocation choice materially affects peer comparisons and valuation multiples.\n\n**Conclusion:** The all-in segment allocation of Starship R&D to Space is technically compliant with ASC 280 segment reporting (the segment CODM uses Adjusted EBITDA as the measure), but it substantially understates the Space segment\'s underlying economic profitability and overstates the cost burden relative to the cross-segment benefits the investment generates. Investors should treat the reported Space segment Adjusted EBITDA as a floor that masks the true earning power of the legacy launch business.\n'})
